# Title: Identify repeating genes in a DNA sequence using Open Reading Frames (ORFs)

# Description:
  - An ORF is a continuous stretch of DNA that begins with a start codon (ATG) and ends with a stop codon (TAA, TAG, or TGA) and represents a potential protein-coding region.
  - We will use NCBI to download DNA sequences in FASTA format. 
  - The code will scan the sequence and identify start and stop codons and thus all possible ORFs in reading frames
  - Once ORFs are identified, the program will compare them to detect repeated or similar ORF sequences, which may indicate repeating genes, gene duplications, or conserved functional regions.
  - The code may also produce a general summary statistics including total number of ORFs, Repeated ORFs, Longest ORF.

# Outcomes:
  - Genome annotation: Researchers can use ORF detection to locate possible protein-coding regions when analyzing newly sequenced genomes.
  - Gene duplication studies: Through repeating genes identification, researchers can study about gene family, disease related mutations, genetic disorders. 
